Then came last month’s six-part documentary series on Lifetime, “Surviving R. Kelly.” Woman after woman faced the camera to tell her harrowing story.
But now, after the Lifetime series, something much bigger happened: His record label, RCA, dropped him.
AD“All of the systems failed — journalism failed, the police failed, the courts failed, the music industry failed, parents failed,” he said.
“The series was like a six-hour version of the New York magazine cover on Bill Cosby,” DeRogatis told me.
(Rogatis’s book, “Soulless: The Case Against R. Kelly,” will be published in June; he has been reporting, most recently, for the New Yorker magazine.)